TY  - JOUR
T1  - Cross-Functional Project Groups in Research and New Product Development: Diversity, Communications, Job Stress, and Outcomes
AU  - Keller, Robert T.
Y1  - 2001/06/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069369
DO  - 10.5465/3069369
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 547
EP  - 555
VL  - 44
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A model of cross-functional project groups was developed and hypotheses were tested in a study of 93 research and new product development groups from four companies. The results showed that functional diversity had indirect effects through external communication on one-year-later measures. Technical quality and schedule and budget performance improved, but group cohesiveness diminished. Functional diversity also had an indirect effect through job stress on group cohesiveness, which was again reduced. Implications for the development of conceptual models of cross-functional groups and their effective management are discussed.
AB  - A model of cross-functional project groups was developed and hypotheses were tested in a study of 93 research and new product development groups from four companies. The results showed that functional diversity had indirect effects through external communication on one-year-later measures. Technical quality and schedule and budget performance improved, but group cohesiveness diminished. Functional diversity also had an indirect effect through job stress on group cohesiveness, which was again reduced. Implications for the development of conceptual models of cross-functional groups and their effective management are discussed.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/3069369
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/3069369
Y2  - 2026/04/24
